qas.question: Which seven CDPs were incorporated as part of the 1982 Census?

context: Of Alaska's 2010 Census population figure of 710,231, 20,429 people, or <a0_0><b3_0><b4_0><b5_0>2.88%<b5_0/><b4_0/><b3_0/><a0_0/> of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place. Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of <a1_0><b6_0>Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla<b6_0/><a1_0/>. CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau, except that seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 Census (<a2_0><b7_0>Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, North Tongass Highway, Pennock Island and Saxman East<b7_0/><a2_0/>), but have not been used since. The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
